snippet.textDisplay: I think I kind of at least try to relate to most of the answer they gave. But one thing threw me off: living in Germany our social security system is one of the most important things the government supports.(i am not saying the german system is perfect but..)When they answered to the question if they should pay more taxes- I kinda agree, they should. I am not a millionaire, in Germany, a millionaire pays the highest "rank" of taxes which is about half their income. I can not image having to give that much away <del>but it is used to support people who are in a worse situation then you are. As most of these millionaires said they came from a broke/poor household, why shouldn't they support the ones which are poor right now? Being honest, as i informed myself about the American social security system, I was kind of shocked. It is -especially compared to some European countries including Germany</del> really bad and non-existent, when it comes to health care. So-as a millionaire in Germany- I would love for them to give more away for taxes, because they have it. That might not make it fair, but it makes the system work and supports others, which is a good thing. As an American, I probably would agree with them, because I do not really know what their taxes are used for. Still, they somehow invest in education, and as a millionaire-why would you not give those taxes away for that? Of course I can not really relate because I am not even close to being a millionaire. Money is hard to earn, I think I know that much. But why would you not be kind and give it away if you have enough?

snippet.textDisplay:
Let me tell y'all something 'bout Timothy Sykes.

*Trying to make an iffy point here

He got his (roughly) $10,000 bar mitzvah money from his family. He use to go to some prestigious university but he said he dropped out because he's been doing stocks and been successful with it. During his time when he was "building his wealth" in the 1990s, he was those people that got rich on "pump and dump" schemes from wallstreet- pump n dump, to put it in layman's terms, is when people get rich from high change in the percentage of what a stock gained or loosed because they were riding the market manipulation from the market players (big banks)- he's now selling stock courses (expensive AF) n regarded by some stock market traders like me as some rip off.

I'm trying to make a point here.
Not everyone is able to HAVE STARTED in a place that got them the resources he was given. Like, I'm very sure he was probably living in his family's wealth- who just gives out 10,000 for bar mitzvah money when a family isn't able to? The first thing the poor does is look for the resources for which they can survive. They're not of the same place when they can simply let their hard earned savings go to high risk stock (which Tim is using- penny stocks) and gamble it all to get rich. Of course he would be willing to risk that 10,000 because he has less to lose. He also gave up an opportunity to which he could get better education, but because he didn't even "need" it, he doesnt.

Mind you, after his profits from the pump and dump from the 1990s, he didn't even show how much he's profitng today. He sells overly expensive courses for people to buy, which are applicable to the 1990s, but how about for the market today??

This guy is a complete joke. He wants to seem honest, but he's an arrogant liar, and out of touch.

WOW...disconnected & lack of insight are two words I would use to describe many of the folks in this episode. Typically, after watching these videos I feel more informed and like I do have a better understanding of a different perspective. This episode just affirmed what I already thought I knew about people who are wealthy.

On an individual basis people may not be poor solely because of the rich, but the wealth inequality in America is a problem. The top 1% possess 40% of the nation’s wealth and if you think it’s just because those people “worked hard” you are grossly mistaken about the way capitalism operates in this country. There are millions of people in this country who get up every morning and “work hard” day after day who are not in the 1% of wealth holders some struggling to maintain middle class status even. There’s so many folks who ‘work hard’ who will never reach this type of status so obviously there’s more factors at play that make people millionaires like luck, circumstance, privilege, who you know etc.

Sorry to say Linda, but your husband’s success does not by any stretch of the imagination disprove or refute wealth inequality in this country.

Don’t even get me started on Tim. Actually, fuck it, I’m going in on him. Did you really just say if you’re paralyzed you can just wheel yourself down the street? You DON’T have a clue the barriers and challenges that present themselves as a person who is differently abled in this country whether it be physically or mentally so fuck out of here with your inability to acknowledge your privilege. Did you seriously just say you wish you could know what it’s like to be poor, but also high five that you haven’t known what it’s like in the same time span?! I wish that for you, too. It might humble your loud, arrogant, brash personality. Also, good for you you went to third world countries to try and discover what it was like to be poor. You didn’t need to do that though because America has people struggling right here you could talk to. But even visiting with poorer folks to try and “find out what it’s like” is so disgusting. Poor people don’t exist so you can gawk at them and try and discover what it’s like to be poor. No. Just no.

There’s more I could say, but I’m already damn near a whole novel in. I’ve never scoffed and eye rolled at a video more.

snippet.textDisplay: The very first question prompt, "I am self made", really demonstrated how large their egos were. If you think about it, no one is self made. The people they are today is a result of all the people and resources that they built off of. Their parents, friends, colleagues, customers, and people they look to for knowledge/advice. These people molded them into who they are. Not to mention being straight up lucky. Being born without any debilitating illnesses or conditions, and being born in the right place at the right time are all huge contributors to their success. Without those people and resources, they would not be standing here today.
